04697nam a22008415i 9780520925120DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209251207 a10.1525/97805209251202doi  a(DE-B1597)542732  a(OCoLC)1163877945  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPA4494.C9 7aPOL0100002bisacsh1 aNadon, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aXenophon's Prince :bRepublic and Empire in the Cyropaedia /cChristopher Nadon.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (211 p.) :b1 vign.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: The Cyropaedia as Political Theory -- t1. Republic -- t2. Transformation -- t3. Empire -- t4. Motives -- t5. Xenophons Intentions -- tWorks Cited -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor over two millennia, the Cyropaedia, an imaginative biography of the Persian king Cyrus the Great, was Xenophon's most popular work and considered his masterpiece. This study contributes to the recent rediscovery of the Cyropaedia and Xenophon, making intelligible the high esteem in which writers of the stature of Machiavelli held Xenophon's works and the importance of his place among classical authors. The ending of the Cyropaedia has presented a notoriously difficult puzzle for scholars. The bulk of the work seems to idealize the career of Cyrus, but the final chapter documents the swift and disastrous degeneration of the empire he founded. This conclusion seems to call his achievements into question. Nadon resolves this long-standing interpretive difficulty and demonstrates for the first time the overall coherence and unity of the Cyropaedia. He elucidates the Xenophontic critique of Cyrus contained within the whole of the work and unearths its analysis of the limitations of both republican and imperial politics.This provocative and original treatment of the Cyropaedia will be a definitive step in restoring the status of this important work. Nadon's lively, insightful study draws upon his deep knowledge and understanding of classical political theory and reveals in the Cyropaedia a subtlety and sophistication overlooked until now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImperialism in literature. 0aImperialismxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPolitical fiction, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreece. 0aRepublicanism in literature. 0aRepublicanismzGreece. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aamazing resourcefulness.  aancient empire.  aancient history.  aclassical author.  aclassical studies.  acyrus the great.  agreat contemporaries.  ahistory theory.  aimaginative biography.  ainterpretive difficulty.  aking cyrus.  aliterary puzzle.  amachiavelli.  aoriginal treatment.  apersian king.  aplatonic dialogues.  apolitical process.  aprovocative.  apublic policy.  asocratic education.  asubtle and sophisticated.  aworks cited.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022404940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520925120?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925120423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520925120/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles